%description:
Regression test for stateless PCEP path computation (RFC 5440 Section 6.5/6.6, Workstream
F4 Phase 2): ~RsvpTe's ingress, configured with computationMode="pce", delegates its
CSPF ERO computation to a co-located ~Pcc, which sends a PCReq to a remote ~Pce and installs
the ERO carried back on the matching PCRep -- instead of calling Ted::calculateShortestPath()
locally (Workstream C6, exercised by the sibling rsvpte_cspf.test with computationMode
left at its "local" default on the exact same topology).

Same ad hoc DIAMOND as rsvpte_cspf.test: LSR1 -> {LSR2, LSR3} -> LSR4, no hosts. The
LSR1-LSR2-LSR4 branch is 600 kbps end to end and the cheaper route by metric (total 2);
the LSR1-LSR3-LSR4 branch is 10 Mbps end to end and the more expensive route by metric
(total 10). The ~Pce runs as LSR4's app[0] (LSR4 is two hops away from the ingress LSR1,
reached over an actual, genuinely multi-hop PCEP TCP session -- not loopback -- exercising
this workstream's whole "the PCE may be remote" premise for real); the ~Pcc runs as LSR1's
app[0]. The PCEP TCP session itself rides on the real IP unicast routes ~LinkStateRouting
already installs into every router's Ipv4 routing table toward every other router's routerId
(see this file's addressing note below) -- the same mechanism any other TCP-based traffic
between LSRs would use; no additional static routing or network configurator is needed on
top of what rsvpte_cspf.test's own topology already provides. Both LSR1's Pcc and LSR4's Pce
consult the SAME (fully converged, "omniscient") Ted every LSR already maintains via
LinkStateRouting, so the PCE's computation is provably identical to what ~RsvpTe's own local
CSPF would have produced on this topology (see rsvpte_cspf.test).

Scenario (same shape as rsvpte_cspf.test, timing pushed out well beyond rsvpte_cspf.test's own
margins to leave headroom for TED convergence, PCEP session establishment, AND -- since the
very first PCEP TCP connection attempt (fired ~10ms into the run, before ~LinkStateRouting has
flooded anything) always finds the PCE's route not-yet-converged and dies with a soft ICMPv4
"destination unreachable" -- one full TCP SYN retransmission (RFC 6298's initial RTO, 3s in
this model, see TCP_TIMEOUT_SYN_REXMIT) before the PCEP session can even start negotiating):
  1. At t=0, tunnel 1 (lspid 100, 500 kbps, permanent) is set up from the static traffic.xml.
     The very first createIngressPSB() attempt(s) legitimately fail (PCEP session not yet
     OPERATIONAL, per the paragraph above) and are retried (via the SAME permanent-path retry
     machinery Workstream C6 already built for "CSPF found no path yet" --
     Pcc::requestPathComputation()'s PENDING/NO_PATH results are deliberately indistinguishable
     from that case, see RsvpTe::createIngressPSB()) until the PCEP session is up and the PCRep
     carries a real ERO. With both branches fully free, the PCE picks the plain-shortest (by
     metric) LSR2 branch, exactly like local CSPF would.
  2. At t=7s (well after tunnel 1 has fully established, including the CAC reservation on
     BOTH of its hops, and after that reservation has flooded to LSR4's Ted too -- LSR4's own
     view of the LSR1-LSR2/LSR2-LSR4 links' free bandwidth must reflect tunnel 1's
     reservation, not some stale/partial view, for the PCE to prune correctly), a scenario
     add-session brings up tunnel 2 (lspid 200, another 500 kbps, permanent). The
     LSR1-LSR2/LSR2-LSR4 links now have only 100 kbps free at priority 7 -- not enough for
     another 500k -- so the PCE's own bandwidth pruning must exclude the entire LSR2 branch
     and compute tunnel 2's ERO via LSR3 instead, proving the PCE (not any local fallback)
     made this decision. (Scheduling tunnel 2 comfortably after tunnel 1's establishment
     matters more here than in rsvpte_cspf.test's local-CSPF version: a remote PCE's
     computation reflects whatever its OWN Ted currently knows, which briefly lags an
     in-flight reservation elsewhere in the network -- unlike local CSPF, which always reads
     the ingress's own, self-consistent Ted. Verified while developing this test: moving
     tunnel 2 to t=5s -- the same instant tunnel 1's OWN first successful attempt lands --
     races tunnel 2's PCReq against tunnel 1's reservation actually being committed anywhere
     yet, so the PCE (correctly, given what it knew at that instant) answers tunnel 2 with the
     stale LSR2-branch ERO; local admission control at the ingress then catches the
     shortfall and retries, and the retry's fresh PCReq gets the correct, pruned answer. That
     is arguably a realistic and even INTERESTING property of a remote PCE (a later phase of
     this workstream could be judged on how gracefully it handles exactly this), but it is not
     what THIS test is about, so t=7s avoids it entirely.)

Asserted:
1. The PCEP session (LSR1's Pcc <-> LSR4's Pce) reaches OPERATIONAL before either tunnel's
   ERO is computed (regex ordering).
2. A PCReq is sent (Pcc-side EV_INFO) and answered by a PCRep carrying a real ERO
   (Pce-side "computed ERO for requestId" EV_INFO, Pcc-side "PCRep received ... ERO with N
   hop(s)" EV_INFO) for both tunnels.
3. The PCE-computed EROs match rsvpte_cspf.test's local-CSPF result hop for hop: tunnel 1 via
   LSR2 (10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2), tunnel 2 via LSR3 (10.1.4.1, 10.1.4.2) -- the bandwidth pruning
   in point 2's scenario step is what forces tunnel 2 off the LSR2 branch, proving it
   happened, on the PCE's side, from the same global TED view a local CSPF call would use
   (manually verified while developing this test: with computationMode left at "local" on
   this exact topology/traffic, rsvpte_cspf.test already proves the identical branch choice
   for both tunnels).
4. Both tunnels actually establish end to end (ingress "Path successfully established").
5. Standard undisposed-object postrun guard.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: PcepCspfDiamond.ned

import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import inet.node.mpls.RsvpMplsRouter;

//
// Ad hoc diamond: LSR1 -> {LSR2 (600 kbps branch), LSR3 (10 Mbps branch)} -> LSR4.
// No hosts -- both tunnels terminate at LSR4 itself. Identical topology/metrics/bandwidths
// to rsvpte_cspf.test's CspfDiamond; LSR1/LSR4 additionally run a PCEP Pcc/Pce pair as
// app[0] (see test.ini), configured entirely from the ini file (no NED changes needed:
// ~RsvpMplsRouter already inherits numApps/app[]/hasTcp from ~ApplicationLayerNodeBase/
// ~Router, and Ted from ~MplsRouterBase).
//
network PcepCspfDiamond
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        LSR1: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,200");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR2: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,300");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR4: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,200");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager {
            @display("p=100,100;is=s");
        }
    connections:
        LSR1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[1];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing (identical to rsvpte_cspf.test): LSR1.ppp0=10.1.1.1 <-> LSR2.ppp0=10.1.1.2
%# (600k branch, hop A); LSR2.ppp1=10.1.2.1 <-> LSR4.ppp0=10.1.2.2 (600k branch, hop B);
%# LSR1.ppp1=10.1.3.1 <-> LSR3.ppp0=10.1.3.2 (10M branch, hop A); LSR3.ppp1=10.1.4.1 <->
%# LSR4.ppp1=10.1.4.2 (10M branch, hop B). routerId="auto" picks the HIGHEST interface
%# address per LSR: LSR1=10.1.3.1, LSR2=10.1.2.1, LSR3=10.1.4.1, LSR4=10.1.4.2. The PCEP
%# session connects to LSR4's routerId (10.1.4.2, its ppp1 address) -- NOT a raw per-hop
%# interface address -- and works over the genuinely multi-hop route ~LinkStateRouting
%# installs (as real Ipv4 routes with real next-hop gateways, e.g. "10.1.4.2/32 via
%# 10.1.4.1") into every router's Ipv4 routing table toward every OTHER router's routerId;
%# there is no separate/manual static routing for the PCEP traffic (unlike a router's
%# individual non-routerId interface addresses, e.g. LSR2's 10.1.1.2, which are NOT
%# individually reachable this way -- only each router's own routerId is).
%# RSVP signaling itself doesn't rely on this at all (a full strict ERO resolves its next
%# hop via the TED directly, never via the Ipv4 routing table), so rsvpte_cspf.test never
%# needed or exercised it; this test is the first to actually route real IP traffic across
%# the diamond.
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.4.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.1.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.1.4.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1_rsvp.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sessions>
	<session>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>

		<paths>
			<path>
				<lspid>100</lspid>
				<bandwidth>500000</bandwidth>
				<permanent>true</permanent>
			</path>
		</paths>
	</session>
</sessions>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: scenario.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<scenario>
	<at t="7s">
		<add-session module="LSR1.rsvp">
			<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
			<tunnel_id>2</tunnel_id>

			<paths>
				<path>
					<lspid>200</lspid>
					<bandwidth>500000</bandwidth>
					<permanent>true</permanent>
				</path>
			</paths>
		</add-session>
	</at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = PcepCspfDiamond
sim-time-limit = 12s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
%# only the rsvp modules (detail, so the PCE/CSPF-computed-ERO EV_DETAIL line is captured)
%# and the PCEP apps (info) log -- keeps the log scoped, same rationale as
%# rsvpte_cspf.test/pcep_session.test. NOTE: per-module cmdenv-log-level overrides are
%# matched in FILE ORDER (first matching pattern wins), so specific overrides MUST be
%# declared before the general catch-all below.
**.LSR*.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.LSR1.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.LSR4.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.cmdenv-log-level = off

**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.LSR4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR4.rt"

**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("LSR1_rsvp.xml")
**.LSR1.rsvp.computeEro = true
**.LSR1.rsvp.computationMode = "pce"
**.LSR1.rsvp.pccModule = "^.app[0]"

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

%# PCEP: LSR1 (ingress) runs the Pcc, LSR4 (two hops away, genuinely remote -- not the
%# ingress and not on tunnel 1's own signaling path) runs the Pce, wired to LSR4's own
%# (fully converged) Ted.
**.LSR1.hasTcp = true
**.LSR1.numApps = 1
**.LSR1.app[0].typename = "Pcc"
**.LSR1.app[0].pceAddress = "10.1.4.2"
%# localAddress = LSR1's own routerId (10.1.3.1): ~Ted/~LinkStateRouting (like a real IGP)
%# only guarantees network-wide reachability to each router's OWN routerId, not to its
%# individual per-link interface addresses (e.g. 10.1.1.1, the address an unspecified bind
%# would otherwise let the outgoing route toward the PCE pick) -- see ~Pcc's "localAddress"
%# doc comment.
**.LSR1.app[0].localAddress = "10.1.3.1"
**.LSR1.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.LSR1.app[0].deadTimer = 10s
**.LSR1.app[0].reconnectInterval = 1s

**.LSR4.hasTcp = true
**.LSR4.numApps = 1
**.LSR4.app[0].typename = "Pce"
**.LSR4.app[0].tedModule = "^.ted"
**.LSR4.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.LSR4.app[0].deadTimer = 10s

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Sanity: the add-session at t=7s actually reached the ingress.
%contains: stdout
adding new session into database
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 1: the PCEP session comes up before the first successfully PCE-computed ERO
%# (ordering regex -- Pcc is the active side, so its Open is sent first; %contains-regex
%# matches with re.DOTALL, so a lone ".*" filler line can absorb any number of
%# intervening lines, same convention as pcep_session.test's own ordering regex).
%contains-regex: stdout
Open sent to PCE .*
.*
PCEP session with .* is now OPERATIONAL
.*
PCE computed ERO for session .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 2: a PCReq is actually sent and answered with a real ERO, both sides.
%contains-regex: stdout
PCReq sent to PCE \(requestId=.*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains-regex: stdout
PCReq received from .* \(requestId=.*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains-regex: stdout
computed ERO for requestId .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains-regex: stdout
PCRep received from PCE: requestId=.*, ERO with .* hop\(s\)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 3: tunnel 1 (lspid 100) via the LSR2 branch (both branches free, cheaper
%# metric) -- LSR2's routerId 10.1.2.1, then LSR4's routerId 10.1.4.2 -- exactly matching
%# rsvpte_cspf.test's local-CSPF result on the identical topology.
%contains: stdout
PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=100): 10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 3 (continued): tunnel 2 (lspid 200) forced onto the LSR3 branch by the PCE's
%# own bandwidth pruning (LSR2 branch has only 100 kbps free at priority 7 after tunnel 1's
%# 500k reservation on BOTH its hops) -- LSR3's routerId 10.1.4.1, then LSR4's 10.1.4.2.
%contains: stdout
PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=200): 10.1.4.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Negative check tied to the pruning above: tunnel 2 must NOT end up on the LSR2 branch
%# (which is exactly what happens if the PCE's bandwidth-pruning silently degenerates into
%# the plain unpruned shortest path -- see rsvpte_cspf.test's own falsification history for
%# this same CSPF call).
%not-contains: stdout
PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.1.4.2, lspid=200): 10.1.2.1, 10.1.4.2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 4: both tunnels actually establish end to end using the PCE-provided path.
%contains: stdout
Path successfully established
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
